16 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
17 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
18 Article – Education
19 11–409.
20 (A) (1) (1) THE COMMISSION SHALL COLLECT STUDENT–LEVEL DATA
21 FROM EACH PUBLIC INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION IN THE STATE ON THE
22 PARENTAL STATUS OF STUDENTS ENROLLED IN EACH INSTITUTION.
23 (2) THE COMMISSION, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE PUBLIC
24 INSTITUTIONS OF HIGHER EDUCATION, SHALL DEVELOP QUESTIONS THAT ALLOW
25 EACH STUDENT TO IDENTIFY:
26 (I) WHETHER THE STUDENT IS A PARENT OR A LEGAL
27 GUARDIAN, ACTING AS A PARENT OR A LEGAL GUARDIAN, OR EXERCISING CARE,
28 CUSTODY, OR CONTROL OVER A CHILD OF ANY AGE;
29 (II) THE AGE OF THE CHILDREN FOR WHICH THE STUDENT HAS
30 RESPONSIBILITY; AND
31 (III) THE TYPE OF CAREGIVING RESPONSIBILITIES THE STUDENT
32 PROVIDES, INCLUDING WHETHER THE STUDENT:
33 1. IS A SINGLE PARENT; OR

SENATE BILL 420 3
1 2. SHARES PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITIES WITH
2 SOMEONE IN THE SAME HOUSEHOLD OR A DIFFERENT HOUSEHOLD.
3 (B) (1) EACH PUBLIC INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION SHALL PLACE
4 THE QUESTIONS DEVELOPED UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION ON ONE OR
5 MORE FORMS THAT ARE USED BY THE INSTITUTION TO COLLECT DEMOGRAPHIC
6 DATA FROM STUDENTS.
7 (2) EACH PUBLIC INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION SHALL MAKE
8 THE DATA COLLECTED UNDER THIS SECTION AVAILABLE TO THE COMMISSION IN
9 ACCORDANCE WITH THE FORMAT DETERMINED BY THE COMMISSION UNDER
10 SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION.
11 (2) THE COMMISSION, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE PUBLIC
12 INSTITUTIONS OF HIGHER EDUCATION, SHALL DEVELOP QUESTIONS THAT ALLOW
13 EACH STUDENT TO IDENTIFY:
14 (I) WHETHER THE STUDENT IS A PARENT OR A LEGAL
15 GUARDIAN, ACTING AS A PARENT OR A LEGAL GUARDIAN, OR EXERCISING CARE,
16 CUSTODY, OR CONTROL OVER A CHILD OF ANY AGE;
17 (II) THE AGE OF THE CHILDREN FOR WHICH THE STUDENT HAS
18 RESPONSIBILITY; AND
19 (III) THE TYPE OF CAREGIVING RESPONSIBILITIES THE
20 STUDENT PROVIDES, INCLUDING WHETHER THE STUDENT:
21 1. IS A SINGLE PARENT; OR
22 2. SHARES PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITIES WITH
23 SOMEONE IN THE SAME HOUSEHOLD OR A DIFFERENT HOUSEHOLD.
24 (B) (1) EACH PUBLIC INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION SHALL PLACE
25 THE QUESTIONS DEVELOPED UNDER SUBSECTION (A) OF THIS SECTION ON ONE OR
26 MORE FORMS THAT ARE USED BY THE INSTITUTION TO COLLECT DEMOGRAPHIC
27 DATA FROM STUDENTS.
28 (2) EACH PUBLIC INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION SHALL MAKE
29 THE DATA COLLECTED UNDER THIS SECTION AVAILABLE TO THE COMMISSION IN
30 ACCORDANCE WITH THE FORMAT DETERMINED BY THE COMMISSION UNDER
31 SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION.

4 SENATE BILL 420
1 (C) (B) (C) THE COMMISSION SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY OUT
2 THIS SECTION, INCLUDING:
3 (1) ESTABLISHING A COMMON FORMAT AND TIME FRAME FOR THE
4 COLLECTION AND REPORTING OF THE DATA REQUIRED UNDER THIS SECTION; AND
5 (2) REQUIRING THE COLLECTION OF PARENTAL STATUS DATA TO BE
6 INCLUDED WITH THE COLLECTION OF OTHER DEMOGRAPHIC DATA.
7 (D) INFORMATION COLLECTED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS SECTION IS NOT
8 CONSIDERED TO BE A MEDICAL OR HEALTH RECORD FOR PURPOSES OF § 24–701(L)
9 OF THIS ARTICLE.
10 (D) (C) (E) ON OR BEFORE SEPTEMBER 1, 2027, AND EACH SEPTEMBER 1
11 THEREAFTER, AND EACH SEPTEMBER 1 THEREAFTER, THE COMMISSION SHALL
12 SUBMIT A REPORT TO THE SENATE BUDGET AND TAXATION COMMITTEE, THE
13 SENATE COMMITTEE ON EDUCATION, ENERGY, AND THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE
14 HOUSE APPROPRIATIONS COMMITTEE, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE
15 STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THAT SUMMARIZES THE DATA COLLECTED BY THE
16 COMMISSION UNDER THIS SECTION.
17 15–140.
18 (a) [(1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
19 (2) “Pregnant] IN THIS SECTION, “PREGNANT, “PREGNANT and
20 parenting student” means a student enrolled at a public [senior higher education]
21 institution OF HIGHER EDUCATION OF HIGHER EDUCATION who:
22 [(i)] (1) (1) Is pregnant; [or]
23 [(ii)] (2) (2) Exercises care, custody, or control over a child[.
24 (3) (i) “Public senior higher education institution” means:
25 1. The constituent institutions of the University System of
26 Maryland;
27 2. Morgan State University; and
28 3. St. Mary’s College of Maryland.
