9 (b) The General Assembly finds that all students at an institution of higher
10 education in the State, regardless of their gender, shall enjoy freedom from discrimination
11 of any kind, including pregnancy discrimination as described in Title IX of the Education
12 Amendments of 1972.
13 (c) (1) Each public [senior higher education] institution OF HIGHER
14 EDUCATION OF HIGHER EDUCATION shall adopt a plan regarding pregnant and
15 parenting students that is consistent with Title IX of the federal Higher Education Act.
16 (2) The plan required under paragraph (1) of this subsection shall include:
17 (i) Referral to on–campus or off–campus services to assist regarding
18 the availability of or eligibility for government assistance programs, including:
19 1. The Special Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program
20 for Women, Infants, and Children;
21 2. The Child Care Scholarship Program;
22 3. The Maryland Medical Assistance Program;
23 4. The Maryland Children’s Health Insurance Program; and
24 5. Any other programs, scholarships, or subsidies for
25 pregnant and parenting students;
26 (ii) The provision of information about or referrals to resources
27 regarding adoption services;
28 (iii) The provision of information about or referrals to resources
29 regarding adoption services;

6 SENATE BILL 420
1 (iii) The availability of institutional accommodations for pregnant
2 and parenting students; and
3 (iv) (III) (iv) A referral network of on–campus and off–campus health
4 care service providers.
5 (d) On or before [August] OCTOBER 1, 2026, each public [senior higher
6 education] institution OF HIGHER EDUCATION OF HIGHER EDUCATION shall post the
7 plan adopted under subsection (c) of this section on the institution’s website.
8 24–701.
9 (l) (1) “Student data” means data relating to or impacting student
10 performance.
11 (2) “Student data” includes:
12 (i) State and national assessments;
13 (ii) Course–taking and completion;
14 (iii) Grade point average;
15 (iv) Remediation;
16 (v) Retention;
17 (vi) Degree, diploma, or credential attainment;
18 (vii) Enrollment;
19 (viii) Demographic data;
20 (ix) Juvenile delinquency records;
21 (x) Elementary and secondary school disciplinary records;
22 (xi) Child welfare data;
23 (xii) License, industry certificate, or vocational certificate;
24 (xiii) Personally identifiable information; [and]
25 (xiv) PARENTAL STATUS; AND
26 (XV) Student disability data by specific disability category.

SENATE BILL 420 7
1 (3) “Student data” does not include:
